fields.label: Volunariness-language
fields.text: It is okay to say no to joining this study. You will not lose any services, benefits, or rights you would normally have at [insert study site] if you decide not to join. If you decide to join the study, it should be because you really want to volunteer.

fields.label: Other_options_not_impacted_language
fields.text: Being in this research will not prevent you from getting your normal medical care or from choosing other options for your care.

fields.label: randomization_canned_language
fields.text: In this study, a computer program will randomly assign you to your study group. That means that you will not choose which study group you are in and that the research team will not choose which study group you are in. You will have equal chances of being put in any study group.

fields.text:
If you get hurt or sick at a study site, we will help you get the care you need. This may include first aid, emergency care, and any follow-up care you need. However, any treatment that occurs because of being in the study will be billed to you or your insurance company. 

If you get hurt or sick and you think it is because of the study, do these things:
- Call your doctor  or if an emergency, call 911
- Give your doctor or ER staff this information:

fields.text: The genetic testing we will do in this study is for research purposes only. We will not return any results to you or tell your doctor about them.

fields.label: CT_gov_mandated_language
fields.text: A description of this clinical trial will be available on http://www.ClinicalTrials.gov. This is required by U.S. law. This website will not include information that can identify you. At most, the website will include a summary of the study results. You can search this website any time.

fields.label: No use for Commercial Profit Language
fields.text: We will not use any samples or biospecimens we collect from you for commercial profit. This means we will not sell your samples.

fields.label: No share in profits language
fields.text: Either we, the study sponsor, or an affiliate may eventually profit from the research done with your samples. You will not share in any profits.

fields.label: No use for future research language
fields.text: No. Your information and samples will be used only for this study. It will not be used for future research, either with or without identifiers.

fields.label: not deidentifying language
fields.text: Since you are not going to deidentify their information, for compliance purposes, you should seek to reconsent participants before you use their information.

fields.label: whole_genome_language
fields.text: Using your samples, we will do a genetic test called whole genome sequencing. This test allows us to see your entire genetic code. This code is what determines things specific to each person, such as hair and eye color and risks for diseases.

fields.label: Yes_share with centralized databases
fields.text:
We may send some of your genetic information to other researchers to use. Your information may be put into scientific or commercial databases, like the one at the National Institutes of Health, for example.

Anything we share would only use a code number instead of your name. But, your genetic information is unique to you. So there is still a risk that someone could link this back to you. The risk of this is very small now, but may change in the future as technology changes. 

Even though we follow safety measures, there is also a small risk that others may find out about your genetic test results. Knowing this could cause you to worry that your results will make it harder for you to get insurance or find a job. But, the Genetic Information Nondiscrimination Act (GINA) is a federal law that protects you from this. It makes it illegal for health insurance companies, most health plans, and many employers to discriminate against you based on your genetic information.

Note: GINA does not apply to other types of insurance such as life, disability, or long-term care insurance. Also, it does not apply to companies with fewer than 15 employees.

fields.label: No Anonymization language
fields.text:
We will protect your information as described in this form. Information that might identify you will be kept in the records.

The local study team will know your name and have access to your information. We will do our best to make sure that no one else knows that you are a part of the study or can match the information we collect with you. 

When we share the results of this study in reports, medical journals, or presentations we will never include your name. It may still be possible for someone to identify you from the information you provide during this study.

fields.label: Not_deidentifying_info_shared_with_sponsor_lang
fields.text: We will share some information about you with the study sponsor. That information may identify you.

fields.label: AR_reportable_disease_language
fields.text:
State law requires us to report to the Arkansas Department of Health (ADH) cases of certain diseases that a sick person could give to someone else. During the study, if we learn you have one of these, we must share your name and contact information with ADH.

State law also requires that we tell the authorities if we learn about possible abuse or that you might hurt yourself or someone else.

We are asking if you want to participate in a research study using a special machine and method called Magnetoencephalography (MEG) to study brain activities during tasks involving language and memory. MEG is the newest, most advanced technology of recording and evaluating the brain while it is awake and working. This recording measures the ongoing function of the brain and it can find the areas of the brain that are related with certain functions such as language and memory.

By doing this study, we hope to learn more about how epilepsy may affect language and memory in children. Memory and language are important areas of your brain that allow you to name or recall an object when you see it. When someone suffers of epilepsy, these memory and language areas may be close to the area that produces the seizures, then functions may be disrupted. MEG imaging may help us to pinpoint and better understand any changes of memory and language functions. To accomplish this, we must obtain information from individuals who suffer from epilepsy when performing language and memory tasks.

The purpose of this research is to find new methods of measuring motor skills in patients who receive deep brain stimulation (DBS) to treat movement disorders. 

In this pilot study, we will determine whether we can reliably measure motor skills in healthy individuals using a video game and a set of sensors that will be placed on the participants hands while they perform the game on a computer or virtual reality (VR) headset. 

This pilot study will provide initial feasibility and calibration data on the use of the sensors to control the game that will eventually be used to assess patients with movement disorders on future studies.
If you have never been diagnosed with a neurological disorder, never had brain surgery, and are between the ages of 18 and 89, then you qualify to participate in this pilot study.
